The trade-off between reaction time and the likelihood of increasing beyond $z$ RWs after the start of DECAFORK is controlled by the choice of $\varepsilon$ and is implicit in Theorems 2 and 3. The smaller $\varepsilon$, the larger the times $T_{
u, 1}$ in Theorem 3, which reflect fewer undesired forks at a given time. Conversely, smaller values for $\varepsilon$ lead to smaller values of the CDFs in Theorem 2, hence to a slower decrease of the product and, thus, a larger delay to fork. This trade-off aligns with numerical experiments for different values of $\varepsilon$, which we depict in Fig. 5. The larger $\varepsilon$, the larger the average number of RWs in the system, but the faster the reaction time. Choosing even smaller values for $\varepsilon$ will likely lead to failures of the system after the second burst failure at time $t=6000$.
